<div id="review_4219909779" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4219909779" />
    <a title="BookOtheDay" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/136647815-bookotheday"><img alt="BookOtheDay" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4219909779?book_show_action=true">Sep 05, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="BookOtheDay" class="user" itemprop="url" name="BookOtheDay" href="/user/show/136647815-bookotheday">BookOtheDay</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4219909779" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4805421031925555397">Warnings for: 1970s era views on women, and maybe lgbtq+ ? Discussions of oppression<br/><br/>This book is presented as a series of conversations/monologues where Lame Deer shares anecdotes and answers what must be common questions about his life and culture. The beginning is more biographical and it ends with Lame Deer doing his best to explain various ceremonies and myths of the Sioux. Lame Deer is a lively and talented storyteller but despite good efforts to explain the intricacies of Sioux culture in </span>
  <span id="freeText4805421031925555397" style="display:none">Warnings for: 1970s era views on women, and maybe lgbtq+ ? Discussions of oppression<br /><br />This book is presented as a series of conversations/monologues where Lame Deer shares anecdotes and answers what must be common questions about his life and culture. The beginning is more biographical and it ends with Lame Deer doing his best to explain various ceremonies and myths of the Sioux. Lame Deer is a lively and talented storyteller but despite good efforts to explain the intricacies of Sioux culture in modern, clear language you still feel that something ineffable is lost in translation. Which is probably for the best, but it is pages and pages of that. <br /><br />It is a great introduction if you are looking to learn more about Sioux culture and customs and want a glance at where they were in the 1970s. It is a very informative book and as the title and back should have told you, contains lots of spiritual content. <br /><br />This book has an epilogue that is the story of a white participant in one of the ceremonies, and it is fascinating. I could read a whole book about his life, sorry to say. Kind of a, say self-absorbed person, but still interesting.<br /><br />Two fascinating slices of life.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4805421031925555397" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


